           <h2>Language</h2>
           <p>New Zealand is a bilingual country with two official languages: English and Māori. Māori, the language of the indigenous Māori people, holds great cultural significance and is increasingly being revitalized. Te Reo Māori is taught in schools and used in ceremonies and media to preserve the language and traditions of the Māori people.</p>

           <h2>Currency</h2>
           <p>The official currency of New Zealand is the New Zealand Dollar (NZD). It is widely used for all transactions, and coins come in denominations of 10c, 20c, 50c, $1, and $2, while banknotes are available in $5, $10, $20, $50, and $100. The New Zealand Dollar is one of the most stable currencies in the Asia-Pacific region.</p>

           <h2>Weather</h2>
           <p>New Zealand experiences a temperate climate with four distinct seasons: summer, autumn, winter, and spring. Summer temperatures range from 20°C to 30°C (68°F to 86°F), while winters can be cold, especially in the South Island, where snowfall is common. The country is known for its frequent rainfall, lush greenery, and mild temperatures, making it a popular destination for outdoor enthusiasts.</p>
